				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">This is how I would do that character, it does not require complicated overlaying, but it does use up 3 palettes:<br /><br /><img src="https://i.imgur.com/Do9JPkb.png" alt="Image" /><br /><br />- Sprite tiles can be mirrored<br />- As Kasumi pointed out, make the arms 1 pixel shorter to use only one sprite for the legs (position it off grid). This is good because it reduces horizontal tile count, reducing the chance for sprite flickering.<br />- Only the sword is positioned on top of the other sprites<br /><br />You could use 2 palettes instead of 3 if you made the shoes black and then used white instead of brown on the second palette, like so:<br /><img src="https://i.imgur.com/kR5xEjx.png" alt="Image" /><br /><br />This optimization balance is the key to good, varied NES graphics. Make the most of your resources, because they are limited.</div>

					
						<div class="postbody"><br />_________________<br /><!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="http://nesrocks.com/blog/superpitfall30th/">http://nesrocks.com/blog/superpitfall30th/</a><!-- m --></div>
